The article reflects on the tenth anniversary of the Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting in Newtown, Connecticut. It emphasizes the need for societal guilt and a moral obligation to pass and enforce laws that can prevent future tragedies. The author mentions the recent signing of the Bipartisan Safer Communities Act, which aims to address issues such as ghost guns and gun trafficking. However, the article argues that more needs to be done, specifically calling for a ban on assault weapons and high-capacity magazines. The author expresses a determination to eliminate these weapons and states that it is possible to do so. The article concludes with a message of prayer for the Sandy Hook families and the lives lost.